#week-title("One", "Isolating the Sulphur Fraction")

=== Core Teaching

In the water work of Years One and Two, the student has worked primarily with
Mercury (the volatile, the spirit-carrying medium of distillation) and Salt (the
fixed residue that receives and holds the volatile). The Sulphur — the
characterising soul-principle, the oily and aromatic fraction — has been present
throughout but has not been deliberately isolated and examined on its own terms.

Month 10 remedies this. The philosophical Sulphur of the water work is the
coloured, oily, aromatic fraction that separates out during careful fractional
distillation of a fermented preparation — or, in some preparations, the distinct
layer that forms above or below the main distillate.

*What the Sulphur fraction looks like.* In a fermented plant distillate, the
Sulphur fraction typically appears as:
- A faint oily sheen on the surface of the distillate (in lower concentrations)
- A visible oil layer floating above the hydrosol (in higher concentrations)
- A coloured fraction — amber, yellow-green, or rust — that rises in the early
  or middle stages of distillation, distinct from the clear first fraction
  (Mercury) and the heavier later fractions

The Sulphur fraction carries the most intense aromatic character of the
preparation. It is the "soul" made visible — the quality that makes this
particular preparation recognisably what it is, that distinguishes Melissa from
Rosemary, fermented plant water from plain distilled water.

*Isolation method.* Using a separatory funnel or careful pipetting, separate
the visible oil layer from the hydrosol. Even in preparations where the
separation is not cleanly visible, the earliest distillate fractions tend to
carry disproportionate Sulphur content — these may be collected separately
for comparison.

*Observational purpose.* The isolated Sulphur fraction is examined by scent,
colour, viscosity, and behaviour (does it mix with water? with alcohol? does
it separate on standing?). These observations are recorded and compared with
the properties of the Mercury fraction from the same preparation.

=== Topics This Week

- The Sulphur fraction in fermented plant distillates: what it is and looks like
- Isolation methods: separatory funnel, careful fractionation
- Sensory analysis of the isolated Sulphur fraction
- Comparing Sulphur and Mercury from the same preparation

#inner-work[
  *The Characterising Force*

  The Sulphur is the soul — the force that makes this preparation distinctively
  itself. Contemplate your own Sulphur: the quality that makes you distinctively
  yourself in the Work. Not your intelligence (Mercury) or your habitual patterns
  (Salt) but the animating character — the passion and the particular flavour of
  your engagement with the alchemical path.

  Has this changed since Year One? Record your observations honestly.
]

